<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="161" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="8.[136,1452,446,797]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,697,554,580]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Distribution in Santa Maria river basin:—</emphasis>
Two species were found, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Link &amp; Otto 1828: 9) Pfeiffer ex Mittler (1844: 124)" authorityName="Pfeiffer ex Mittler" authorityPageNumber="124" authorityYear="1844" baseAuthorityName="Link &amp; Otto" baseAuthorityPageNumber="9" baseAuthorityYear="1828" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Gymnocalycium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="8" pageNumber="161" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="denudatum">
<emphasis box="[983,1296,554,580]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Gymnocalycium denudatum</emphasis>
(Link &amp; Otto 1828: 9) Pfeiffer ex 
<bibRefCitation author="Mittler, L." box="[372,592,590,616]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161" pagination="124" refId="ref9125" refString="Mittler, L. (1844) Taschenbch fur Cactusliebliebhaber, Lei Mittler, L. (1844). Taschenbch fur Cactusliebliebhaber, Leipzig 2: 124." type="journal article" year="1844">Mittler (1844: 124)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[610,703,590,616]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[136,229,1940,1962]" captionTargetBox="[306,1282,609,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-168@7.[302,1286,605,1916]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. A) Cereus hildmaninanus (whitish-pink flowers). B) Echinopsis oxygona (pink flowers). C) Frailea albifusca. D) Frailea castanea. E) Frailea albifusca.F) Frailea lepida.G) Frailea mammifera. H) Frailea pumila. I) Frailea pygmaea.J) Frailea erythracantha K) Gymnocalycium denudatum (white flowers). L) Gymnocalycium uruguayense (yellow flowers). Pictures by A. S. Oliveira." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415611/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Fig. 2K</figureCitation>
), and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Arechavaletae 1905: 218) Britton &amp; Rose (1922: 172)" authorityName="Britton &amp; Rose" authorityPageNumber="172" authorityYear="1922" baseAuthorityName="Arechavaletae" baseAuthorityPageNumber="218" baseAuthorityYear="1905" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Gymnocalycium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="8" pageNumber="161" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="uruguayense">
<emphasis box="[774,954,591,617]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">G. uruguayense</emphasis>
(Arechavaletae 1905: 218) 
<bibRefCitation author="Britton, N. L. &amp; Rose, J. N." pageId="8" pageNumber="161" refId="ref7972" refString="Britton, N. L. &amp; Rose, J. N. (1922) The Cactaceae. Descriptions and Illustrations of Plants of the Cactus Family, vols. 3 - 4 Carnegie Institution, Washington, 322 pp." type="book" year="1922">Britton &amp; Rose (1922: 172)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[286,374,626,652]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[136,229,1940,1962]" captionTargetBox="[306,1282,609,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-168@7.[302,1286,605,1916]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. A) Cereus hildmaninanus (whitish-pink flowers). B) Echinopsis oxygona (pink flowers). C) Frailea albifusca. D) Frailea castanea. E) Frailea albifusca.F) Frailea lepida.G) Frailea mammifera. H) Frailea pumila. I) Frailea pygmaea.J) Frailea erythracantha K) Gymnocalycium denudatum (white flowers). L) Gymnocalycium uruguayense (yellow flowers). Pictures by A. S. Oliveira." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415611/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Fig. 2L</figureCitation>
), they are widespread in the study area and grow on rocky outcrops and the Saxon vegetation, tolerate low light.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[136,1452,446,797]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,449,698,724]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Morphologic notes:—</emphasis>
These are usually solitary or clustered plants, globose of more than 
<quantity box="[1197,1251,698,725]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="161" unit="cm" value="4.0">4 cm</quantity>
in diameter, 4–15 sides, bell-shaped, white calyx, pink or yellowish-white flowers. Dried or fleshy fruits up to 
<quantity box="[1209,1266,734,761]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="161" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
in length. They usually bloom from October to December, bearing fruit soon after.
</paragraph>
